    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>The most consequential drug class of the past decade wasn't developed by a neuroscience lab. It wasn't targeting the brain at all.</p>

      <p>GLP-1 receptor agonists — semaglutide, sold as Ozempic for diabetes and Wegovy for obesity; tirzepatide, sold as Mounjaro and Zepbound — were engineered to mimic glucagon-like peptide 1, a gut hormone that stimulates insulin secretion in response to food. The original pharmacological story was clean and metabolic: more GLP-1 signaling, better blood sugar control, secondary weight loss from reduced appetite.</p>

      <p>The clinical story that emerged was considerably stranger. Patients weren't just losing weight. They were losing interest in alcohol. In gambling. In smoking. In the compulsive shopping and nail-biting and obsessive eating patterns that had structured their lives for years. They were describing, in interviews and support groups and social media posts, a quieting of something they began calling "food noise" — a constant, intrusive cognitive commentary about eating that had apparently always been there and that they had, until its absence, taken to be a normal feature of human consciousness.</p>

      <p>It wasn't.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-glp1-system-in-the-brain" class="reveal">
      <h2>The GLP-1 System in the Brain</h2>

      <p>GLP-1 is produced in the gut in response to food intake, but it is also produced in the brainstem — specifically in neurons of the nucleus tractus solitarius, the same structure where vagal afferents terminate. GLP-1 receptors are expressed throughout the brain, including in the hypothalamus (appetite regulation), the ventral tegmental area (the core of the dopaminergic reward circuit), the nucleus accumbens (reward processing and motivation), and the prefrontal cortex (executive control and decision-making).</p>

      <p>This distribution was known before Ozempic existed. What was not appreciated was how pharmacologically activating these receptors with a long-acting, highly potent agonist would translate into observable human behavior.</p>

      <p>The short answer is: it reduces the motivational salience of rewarding stimuli. The brain on semaglutide finds food less compelling — not unpleasant, not aversive, just less worth thinking about. The compelling quality, which for some people is nearly constant, dims. The silence this creates is, apparently, striking enough that patients who have never questioned their relationship with food begin to realize that what they'd experienced as normal hunger and normal wanting was something elevated well beyond baseline.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"Patients described a quieting of something they called 'food noise' — a constant, intrusive cognitive commentary about eating that they had, until its absence, taken to be a normal feature of human consciousness."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="the-food-noise-phenomenon" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Food Noise Phenomenon</h2>

      <p>The "food noise" reports began appearing in patient communities and clinical interviews around 2023-2024, as long-term users accumulated enough experience to describe qualitative changes in cognition rather than simply noting weight loss.</p>

      <p>The descriptions were strikingly consistent across demographically diverse populations. Patients reported that intrusive thoughts about food — what they would eat, when, where, what they were looking forward to — occupied a significant portion of their daily cognitive bandwidth before the drug, and that this commentary substantially diminished within weeks of beginning treatment. Some described it as finally being able to think about other things.</p>

      <p>The clinical interpretation of this has evolved. The initial assumption was that the drug was reducing appetite signals from the gut, which the brain then processed passively. The emerging picture is more active: GLP-1 receptors in the mesolimbic dopamine system appear to modulate the reward value assigned to food-related cues. The drug doesn't make people less hungry in the simple sense; it reduces how much the prospect of eating occupies motivational processing.</p>

      <p>This distinction matters because motivational salience is not limited to food. The same dopaminergic circuitry that makes food compelling also makes alcohol, nicotine, gambling, and most addictive behaviors compelling. If GLP-1 receptor activation uniformly reduces the reward-cue salience in this system, the effects on addiction would follow logically.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-addiction-signal" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Addiction Signal</h2>

      <p>The data on GLP-1 drugs and addictive behavior has accumulated faster than any mechanistic understanding of it.</p>

      <p><strong>Alcohol.</strong> Multiple large observational studies have found that patients on GLP-1 agonists show significantly reduced alcohol consumption — reductions of 30-50% in weekly drinks in some cohorts. Controlled animal studies confirm the mechanism: rodents with access to alcohol voluntarily reduce intake after receiving GLP-1 agonists. A human pilot trial of semaglutide for alcohol use disorder showed substantial reductions in cravings and drinking days. A larger clinical trial is underway. Preliminary neuroimaging data suggests the drug reduces activation in reward circuits in response to alcohol cues — the same cues that drive craving.</p>

      <p><strong>Smoking.</strong> Studies examining smoking rates among patients on GLP-1 drugs have found higher cessation rates than matched control groups. Survey data from patients shows a consistent pattern of reporting reduced nicotine craving and reduced pleasure from smoking. Mechanistic studies suggest nicotine and GLP-1 act on overlapping neural circuits, and that GLP-1 receptor activation may reduce the dopamine release that gives nicotine its rewarding quality.</p>

      <p><strong>Other compulsive behaviors.</strong> Reports from patients and clinicians have also described reductions in compulsive gambling, compulsive shopping, nail-biting, and skin picking — behaviors with varying levels of addictive overlap but sharing an impulsive, reward-seeking quality. These reports are currently anecdotal at scale, though consistent enough to have generated active research interest. The OCD and binge eating disorder communities have both noted anecdotal improvement in patients who began GLP-1 treatment for metabolic indications.</p>
    </section>

