    <section id="the-gastrointestinal-reality" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Gastrointestinal Reality</h2>

      <p>The brain story has attracted the most scientific interest, but the drug's most common adverse effects are emphatically not neurological.</p>

      <p>Nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, and gastric discomfort affect a substantial proportion of users, particularly in the dose-escalation phase. These effects typically diminish with time but do not disappear for everyone. In rare cases, more serious gastrointestinal events — including gastroparesis, a condition in which stomach emptying is severely delayed — have been reported, and litigation is ongoing regarding whether the drug manufacturers adequately disclosed this risk.</p>

      <p>There is also an under-discussed issue with muscle loss. The rapid weight loss produced by GLP-1 drugs involves loss of fat and lean mass. Without deliberate resistance training and adequate protein intake, patients may lose significant muscle alongside fat — an outcome that is particularly consequential for older adults, for whom muscle mass is a primary predictor of mortality and functional independence. The scale moves in a favorable direction while the body composition changes in a way the scale doesn't capture.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-unanswered-questions" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Unanswered Questions</h2>

      <p>The GLP-1 drug class is, pharmacologically, an experiment being run at scale on hundreds of millions of people, most of whom are taking a drug that affects multiple brain reward circuits for the first time. The long-term neurological consequences — beyond what the multi-year trial data covers — are genuinely unknown.</p>

      <p>Specific unresolved questions include:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Whether chronic GLP-1 receptor agonism causes receptor downregulation, and what that would mean for both therapeutic efficacy and baseline reward processing.</li>
        <li>Whether the anhedonia reports represent a dose-dependent pharmacological effect that could be optimized away or a feature of the mechanism itself.</li>
        <li>Whether people who stop the drugs after years of use experience a rebound in reward-seeking behavior that exceeds their pre-drug baseline.</li>
        <li>Whether the effects on addiction circuitry can be harnessed therapeutically for alcohol use disorder, nicotine dependence, and other conditions at doses and formulations calibrated for those uses rather than for weight loss.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The drugs are remarkable. The confidence with which the public and the medical establishment have embraced them outpaces the evidence on their long-term consequences by a measurable margin. That isn't an argument against their use — the metabolic benefits for severely obese and diabetic patients are substantial and well-documented. It is an argument for intellectual honesty about how much remains unknown.</p>

      <p>The brain hasn't been studied as long as the pancreas. And it turns out the drug cares considerably about both.</p>
    </section>

